% Title Page Information
\title{Strain-Induced Flat Bands and Lateral Heterostructures: \ Hole Localization in Rippled Monolayer TMDs}
\author{Meshal Alawein}
\degreesemester{Spring}
\degreeyear{2025}
\degree{Doctor of Philosophy}
\chair{Professor Ali Javey}
\othermembers{Professor Daryl Chrzan \\
Professor Boubacar Kant\'e}
\numberofmembers{3}
\field{Electrical Engineering and Computer Sciences}
% Front Matter
\maketitle
\approvalpage
\copyrightpage
\chapter*{Abstract}
This thesis explores how periodic rippling in 2D group-VI TMD monolayers---such as MoS\textsubscript{2}, WS\textsubscript{2}, MoSe\textsubscript{2}, and WSe\textsubscript{2}---can flatten their electronic bands under compression. Through first-principles simulations, we trace the formation of periodic ripples and show that, beyond a certain compression, flat valence bands emerge in these otherwise semiconducting TMDs.\ In particular, a gradual mechanical-electronic transition unfolds:\ initial deformation leads to buckling, which triggers the formation of ripples---much like a thin sheet forced to bend under pressure.\ As the compression increases, the valence band evolves in character.\ The $\Gamma$-point (which hosts a nearly flat segment along the $\overline{\Gamma X}$ direction) rises in energy, while the K-point (initially the valence band maximum) drops.\ At a critical compression, these levels cross---signaling the birth of a flat valence band and a fundamental shift in the material’s electronic properties.\ What results is a built-in lateral potential landscape---a heterostructure embedded within a single, chemically uniform monolayer, achieved without chemical doping, stacking, or twist-angle engineering.\ Curvature drives this transformation, and the outcome is striking:\ heave-hole are pinned in high-curvature regions, while electrons remain free to move.\ This asymmetry opens new possibilities for exciton trapping, hole-based electronics, and the study of correlated electronic phases in 2D systems.

